## Records (Java 16+)

Records are immutable data carriers — they automatically generate `equals()`, `hashCode()`, `toString()`, and accessor methods.

```java
// Before records
public class Point {
    private final int x;
    private final int y;
    public Point(int x, int y) { this.x = x; this.y = y; }
    public int x() { return x; }
    public int y() { return y; }
    // equals, hashCode, toString boilerplate...
}

// With records — one line!
public record Point(int x, int y) {}

// Usage
Point p = new Point(3, 4);
p.x(); // 3
```

Records can have custom constructors (compact constructors), implement interfaces, and have static members. They **cannot** extend classes or be subclassed.

## Sealed Classes (Java 17+)

Sealed classes restrict which classes can extend them — enabling **exhaustive pattern matching**.

```java
public sealed interface Shape
    permits Circle, Rectangle, Triangle {}

public record Circle(double radius) implements Shape {}
public record Rectangle(double w, double h) implements Shape {}
public record Triangle(double base, double height) implements Shape {}

// Compiler knows all possible subtypes!
double area = switch (shape) {
    case Circle c    -> Math.PI * c.radius() * c.radius();
    case Rectangle r -> r.w() * r.h();
    case Triangle t  -> 0.5 * t.base() * t.height();
    // No default needed — exhaustive!
};
```

## Pattern Matching

### instanceof pattern (Java 16+)
```java
// Old way
if (obj instanceof String) {
    String s = (String) obj;
    System.out.println(s.length());
}

// Pattern matching
if (obj instanceof String s) {
    System.out.println(s.length()); // s is already cast
}
```

### Switch expressions with patterns (Java 21)
```java
Object obj = ...
String result = switch (obj) {
    case Integer i when i > 0 -> "positive int: " + i;
    case Integer i            -> "non-positive int: " + i;
    case String s             -> "string: " + s;
    case null                 -> "null";
    default                   -> "other";
};
```

## Virtual Threads (Java 21 — Project Loom)

Virtual threads are **lightweight threads managed by the JVM** instead of the OS. They enable millions of concurrent threads with minimal memory overhead.

```java
// Platform thread — expensive, maps 1:1 to OS thread
Thread t = new Thread(() -> doWork());

// Virtual thread — cheap, JVM manages scheduling
Thread vt = Thread.ofVirtual().start(() -> doWork());

// With executor
try (var executor = Executors.newVirtualThreadPerTaskExecutor()) {
    IntStream.range(0, 1_000_000).forEach(i ->
        executor.submit(() -> handleRequest(i)));
}
```

### Why it matters:
- Old model: 1 request = 1 platform thread (expensive, ~2MB each)
- New model: 1 request = 1 virtual thread (~few KB each)
- No need for reactive/async programming for I/O concurrency
- **Write blocking code, get async performance**
